      "content": "Libertarians and anarcho-capitalists, like Murray Rothbard, argue that the state's role in regulating speech is inherently coercive and an infringement on individual liberty. They believe that the market, not the government, should determine the value and distribution of information. Rothbard contends that the state lacks the moral authority to police digital speech because it violates the non-aggression principle, which states that individuals should not initiate force against others. They see the internet as a natural extension of this principle, where individuals should be free to communicate without government interference. Furthermore, they argue that any attempt to regulate speech online is a slippery slope towards censorship and authoritarianism, ultimately undermining the very freedoms that the internet was created to protect.",
